5:42:47 AM [express] POST /api/mealplan 200 in 58715ms :: {"week_summary":"20-year-old moderately active Indian male (170 cm, 65 kg, BMI 22.5) with vata-dominant constitution aiming to support heart health with ~2500 kcal/day, no medical conditions or dietary restrictions.","hydration":"Aim for about 2.5ÔÇô3 liters of water/herbal fluids per day; for vata and heart health, favor warm water or light herbal teas (ginger, fennel, tulsi) sipped regularly rather than large cold drinks.","weekly_strategy":"Meals emphasize warm, lightly spiced, home-cooked Indian dishes with whole grains, plenty of vegetables, legumes, nuts, and heart-healthy fats (rice bran/olive oil) to balance vata and support cardiovascular health. Sodium and deep-fried foods are kept moderate while focusing on soluble fiber (oats, barley, pulses), antioxidants (amla, pomegranate, colorful vegetables), and stable meal timing. Each day is structured around 3 balanced meals and 2 snacks to keep vata grounded, support steady energy, and avoid excessive hunger spikes that stress the cardiovascular system.","clinician_note":"","days":[{"day":1,"day_name":"Monday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Masala Vegetable Oats Upma","ingredients":["rolled oats","rice bran oil","mustard seeds","curry leaves","onion","carrot","green peas","grated beetroot","turmeric powder","ginger","coriander leaves","salt (limited)","water"],"portion":"1 medium bowl ~300 g","macros":{"protein":"10g","carbs":"45g","fat":"8g","calories":"310 kcal"},"why":"Warm, soft oats with vegetables calm vata and provide soluble fiber, which supports heart health by improving lipid profile and satiety.","substitutions":["Use barley flakes instead of oats","Use olive oil instead of rice bran oil"]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Apple-Amla Mint Chutney Slice","ingredients":["apple","fresh amla (Indian gooseberry)","fresh mint leaves","black salt (pinch)","roasted cumin powder","water (for blending chutney)"],"portion":"1 medium apple + 2 tbsp chutney ~180 g","macros":{"protein":"1g","carbs":"30g","fat":"0g","calories":"120 kcal"},"why":"Apple and amla provide pectin and vitamin C for cardiovascular protection, while mint and cumin aid digestion and are gentle for vata.","substitutions":["Use guava instead of apple","Use coriander leaves instead of mint"]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Brown Rice with Moong Dal Tadka and Pumpkin-Drumstick Sabzi","ingredients":["brown rice","split moong dal","pumpkin cubes","drumstick (moringa pods)","onion","tomato","garlic","ginger","turmeric powder","coriander powder","cumin seeds","mustard seeds","rice bran oil","coriander leaves","salt (limited)","water"],"portion":"Brown rice 1 cup cooked (~150 g) + moong dal 1 bowl (~200 g) + sabzi 1 bowl (~150 g)","macros":{"protein":"22g","carbs":"80g","fat":"10g","calories":"520 kcal"},"why":"Moong dal and brown rice form a light yet grounding complete protein, while pumpkin and drumstick offer potassium, fiber, and antioxidants favorable for heart health and vata balance.","substitutions":["Use quinoa instead of brown rice","Use masoor dal instead of moong dal"]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Roasted Masala Chana with Warm Jeera Water","ingredients":["roasted whole chana (black chickpeas)","onion (finely chopped, optional)","tomato (finely chopped, small amount)","coriander leaves","lemon juice (few drops)","cumin seeds","water","black salt (pinch)","chilli powder (optional, small pinch)"],"portion":"Roasted chana 30 g (~1/4 cup) + warm jeera water 1 cup (200 ml)","macros":{"protein":"6g","carbs":"18g","fat":"2g","calories":"120 kcal"},"why":"Roasted chana provides plant protein and fiber for heart health, while warm cumin water aids digestion and keeps vata grounded without heavy fats.","substitutions":["Use boiled chana instead of roasted if you prefer softer texture","Use coriander seed water instead of jeera water"]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"Soft Phulka with Palak-Toor Dal and Carrot- Beet Raita","ingredients":["whole wheat flour","water","toor dal","spinach (palak)","onion","tomato","garlic","ginger","turmeric powder","cumin seeds","rice bran oil","curd (low-fat yogurt)","grated carrot","grated beetroot","roasted cumin powder","coriander leaves","salt (limited)"],"portion":"2 phulkas (~70 g) + dal 1 bowl (~200 g) + raita 1 small bowl (~100 g)","macros":{"protein":"20g","carbs":"65g","fat":"9g","calories":"480 kcal"},"why":"Warm dal, soft phulkas, and probiotic raita are soothing for vata, while leafy greens and legumes support vascular health with folate, potassium, and fiber.","substitutions":["Use masoor dal instead of toor dal","Use bottle gourd in dal instead of spinach"]}}},{"day":2,"day_name":"Tuesday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Moong Dal Chilla Stuffed with Spiced Paneer and Vegetables","ingredients":["split yellow moong dal (soaked and ground)","water","turmeric powder","ginger","green chili (optional, small)","paneer (reduced-fat, crumbled)","grated carrot","finely chopped capsicum","onion","coriander leaves","rice bran oil","salt (limited)"],"portion":"2 medium stuffed chillas (~250 g total)","macros":{"protein":"18g","carbs":"32g","fat":"10g","calories":"330 kcal"},"why":"Moong chilla with paneer gives high-quality protein and is light yet satisfying for vata, supporting lean mass and heart health without excessive saturated fat.","substitutions":["Use grated tofu instead of paneer","Use olive oil instead of rice bran oil"]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Pomegranate and Walnut Bowl","ingredients":["pomegranate arils","walnut halves","black pepper (pinch)"],"portion":"1/2 cup pomegranate (~90 g) + 6 walnut halves (~15 g)","macros":{"protein":"3g","carbs":"18g","fat":"10g","calories":"170 kcal"},"why":"Pomegranate polyphenols and omega-3-rich walnuts are powerful for cardiovascular health, while the combination of sweet and slightly astringent taste is acceptable for vata in small portions.","substitutions":["Use pistachios instead of walnuts","Use orange segments instead of pomegranate"]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Jeera Brown Rice with Rajma Masala and Beet-Carrot Thoran","ingredients":["brown rice","cumin seeds","rajma (kidney beans, soaked and cooked)","onion","tomato","ginger","garlic","turmeric powder","coriander powder","garam masala (small amount)","rice bran oil","grated beetroot","grated carrot","fresh coconut (small, optional)","mustard seeds","curry leaves","salt (limited)","coriander leaves"],"portion":"Jeera brown rice 1 cup cooked (~150 g) + rajma 1 bowl (~200 g) + thoran 1 small bowl (~100 g)","macros":{"protein":"20g","carbs":"85g","fat":"11g","calories":"540 kcal"},"why":"Rajma and brown rice provide complex carbs, protein, and fiber that improve cholesterol and glycemic response, while beet and carrot add heart-friendly nitrates and antioxidants, with warm cooking to pacify vata.","substitutions":["Use barley instead of brown rice","Use masoor-rajma mixed dal instead of plain rajma"]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Steamed Methi-Masala Corn Cups","ingredients":["sweet corn kernels (boiled)","fresh methi leaves (fenugreek, chopped)","onion (finely chopped)","tomato (finely chopped, small)","lemon juice","black pepper","chili flakes (optional)","salt (limited)"],"portion":"1 small bowl ~120 g","macros":{"protein":"4g","carbs":"25g","fat":"2g","calories":"130 kcal"},"why":"Corn provides quick energy while methi brings soluble fiber and mild bitterness helpful for lipids, and steaming keeps it light for vata digestion.","substitutions":["Use green peas instead of corn","Add a spoon of boiled moong for extra protein"]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"One-Pot Vegetable Quinoa Khichdi with Ghee Tadka","ingredients":["quinoa","split moong dal","carrot","bottle gourd (lauki)","green peas","ginger","turmeric powder","cumin seeds","mustard seeds","curry leaves","small amount of ghee","salt (limited)","coriander leaves","water"],"portion":"1 large bowl ~300 g","macros":{"protein":"16g","carbs":"55g","fat":"8g","calories":"380 kcal"},"why":"Quinoa-moong khichdi is warm, soft, and easy to digest for vata, combining high-quality protein, magnesium, and fiber to protect heart health.","substitutions":["Use barley instead of quinoa","Use rice bran oil instead of ghee for a fully plant-based option"]}}},{"day":3,"day_name":"Wednesday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Soft Idli with Sambar (Drumstick & Pumpkin) and Coconut-Coriander Chutney","ingredients":["idli batter (rice and urad dal fermented)","drumstick pieces","pumpkin cubes","toor dal","onion","tomato","sambar powder (moderate)","tamarind pulp (small amount)","turmeric powder","mustard seeds","curry leaves","rice bran oil","fresh coconut","coriander leaves","green chili (small, optional)","salt (limited)","water"],"portion":"3 small idlis (~180 g) + sambar 1 bowl (~150 g) + chutney 2 tbsp (~30 g)","macros":{"protein":"13g","carbs":"58g","fat":"9g","calories":"380 kcal"},"why":"Fermented, soft idli is light and vata-friendly, while sambar with drumstick and pumpkin adds fiber, minerals, and plant protein for a heart-protective start.","substitutions":["Use rava idli batter instead of rice idli batter","Use bottle gourd instead of pumpkin in sambar"]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Orange Wedges with Amla-Ginger Shot","ingredients":["orange","amla juice (freshly extracted or grated amla squeezed)","grated ginger","honey (1/2 tsp, optional)","water"],"portion":"1 medium orange (~130 g) + 30 ml amla-ginger shot diluted in 30 ml water","macros":{"protein":"2g","carbs":"22g","fat":"0g","calories":"90 kcal"},"why":"Citrus and amla provide vitamin C and antioxidants that support blood vessel integrity and immunity, while ginger improves circulation without aggravating vata when used mildly.","substitutions":["Use sweet lime (mosambi) instead of orange","Skip honey if avoiding added sugars"]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Jowar Roti with Mixed Veg Curry (Okra, Peas, Carrot) and Salad","ingredients":["jowar flour","warm water","okra (bhindi)","green peas","carrot","onion","tomato","garlic","ginger","turmeric powder","coriander powder","rice bran oil","coriander leaves","lemon juice","cucumber","salt (limited)"],"portion":"2 jowar rotis (~90 g) + veg curry 1.5 bowls (~220 g) + small salad (~80 g)","macros":{"protein":"14g","carbs":"70g","fat":"10g","calories":"460 kcal"},"why":"Jowar is a heart-healthy millet rich in fiber and antioxidants, while okra and peas give soluble fiber that aids cholesterol control and the cooked meal soothes vata.","substitutions":["Use bajra roti instead of jowar roti","Use methi leaves in curry instead of peas"]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Warm Spiced Guava Compote with Cinnamon","ingredients":["ripe guava (peeled and chopped)","water","cinnamon stick or powder","black pepper (pinch)","jaggery (very small, optional)"],"portion":"1 small bowl cooked guava ~120 g","macros":{"protein":"2g","carbs":"20g","fat":"0g","calories":"80 kcal"},"why":"Lightly stewed guava with cinnamon is easier for vata to digest, provides vitamin C and fiber for heart health, and avoids raw roughness that can disturb vata.","substitutions":["Use apple instead of guava","Use cardamom instead of cinnamon"]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"Masoor Dal with Bottle Gourd and Soft Rice","ingredients":["masoor dal","bottle gourd (lauki) cubes","onion","tomato","garlic","ginger","turmeric powder","cumin seeds","rice bran oil","coriander leaves","white rice (short-grain preferred, well cooked)","salt (limited)","water"],"portion":"Rice 1 cup cooked (~150 g) + dal 1.5 bowls (~250 g)","macros":{"protein":"18g","carbs":"75g","fat":"7g","calories":"460 kcal"},"why":"Masoor dal and soft rice create a comforting, protein-rich meal that is easy on vata digestion, while lauki adds potassium and fluid-rich fiber beneficial for blood pressure and heart health.","substitutions":["Use moong dal instead of masoor","Use brown rice if digestion is strong"]}}},{"day":4,"day_name":"Thursday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Vegetable Poha with Peanuts and Curry Leaves","ingredients":["thick poha (flattened rice)","onion","carrot","green peas","potato cubes (small amount)","mustard seeds","curry leaves","turmeric powder","green chili (optional, small)","peanuts (roasted)","rice bran oil","lemon juice","coriander leaves","salt (limited)","water for rinsing poha"],"portion":"1 medium plate ~250 g","macros":{"protein":"9g","carbs":"55g","fat":"10g","calories":"370 kcal"},"why":"Warm, moist poha with vegetables and a few peanuts is light yet grounding for vata, providing complex carbs and healthy fats for heart health without heaviness.","substitutions":["Use sprouts instead of peanuts if you prefer","Use bottle gourd instead of potato"]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Buttermilk with Roasted Cumin and Coriander","ingredients":["low-fat curd","water","roasted cumin powder","chopped coriander leaves","black salt (pinch)"],"portion":"1 glass ~200 ml","macros":{"protein":"4g","carbs":"6g","fat":"2g","calories":"55 kcal"},"why":"Lightly spiced buttermilk supports digestion and hydration, calms vata, and offers a low-fat calcium source beneficial for cardiovascular and bone health.","substitutions":["Use plain warm milk (low-fat) with turmeric if avoiding buttermilk","Use plant-based yogurt if dairy is not desired"]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Barley Khichda with Mixed Lentils and Vegetables","ingredients":["pearled barley","mixed dals (moong, masoor, toor)","bottle gourd (lauki)","carrot","green peas","onion","ginger","garlic","turmeric powder","cumin seeds","small amount of ghee or rice bran oil","salt (limited)","coriander leaves","water"],"portion":"1 large bowl ~320 g","macros":{"protein":"20g","carbs":"70g","fat":"8g","calories":"440 kcal"},"why":"Barley is excellent for heart health due to its beta-glucan fiber, and cooking it as a soft khichda with lentils and vegetables makes it suitable for vata.","substitutions":["Use broken wheat (dalia) instead of barley","Use olive oil instead of ghee"]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Sprouted Moong Chat (Lightly Steamed)","ingredients":["sprouted moong","onion (small amount, finely chopped)","tomato (small amount, chopped)","coriander leaves","lemon juice","black pepper","salt (limited)"],"portion":"1 small bowl ~100 g","macros":{"protein":"7g","carbs":"16g","fat":"1g","calories":"100 kcal"},"why":"Lightly steamed sprouts provide high-quality plant protein and fiber that support lipid metabolism, while steaming reduces vata-aggravating rawness.","substitutions":["Use boiled chana instead of sprouts","Add grated carrot instead of onion if you prefer milder taste"]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"Soft Bajra Khichdi with Vegetables and Tempered Garlic","ingredients":["bajra flour (or broken bajra)","split moong dal","carrot","peas","onion","garlic","ginger","turmeric powder","cumin seeds","rice bran oil","salt (limited)","water","coriander leaves"],"portion":"1 large bowl ~300 g","macros":{"protein":"15g","carbs":"60g","fat":"7g","calories":"380 kcal"},"why":"Bajra is warming and grounding for vata, and cooking it as a soft khichdi with moong and vegetables keeps it heart-friendly and easy to digest.","substitutions":["Use jowar instead of bajra","Use small amount of ghee instead of oil for flavor if tolerated"]}}},{"day":5,"day_name":"Friday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Stuffed Vegetable Paratha (Methi, Carrot, Peas) with Low-Fat Curd","ingredients":["whole wheat flour","water","fresh methi leaves (chopped)","grated carrot","boiled green peas","ginger","cumin powder","turmeric powder","rice bran oil (for cooking)","low-fat curd","salt (limited)"],"portion":"2 small stuffed parathas (~180 g) + curd 1/2 cup (~100 g)","macros":{"protein":"14g","carbs":"60g","fat":"11g","calories":"430 kcal"},"why":"Warm stuffed parathas with methi and vegetables are grounding and satisfying for vata, while using minimal oil and curd keeps it heart-conscious with added fiber and protein.","substitutions":["Use paneer as part of the stuffing instead of peas","Dry roast parathas with no oil and brush lightly with ghee for a different fat profile"]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Mixed Nuts and Seeds Handful","ingredients":["almonds (soaked and peeled)","pistachios (unsalted)","walnuts","sunflower seeds"],"portion":"1 small handful ~20 g (about 4 almonds, 4 pistachios, 2 walnut halves, 1 tsp seeds)","macros":{"protein":"4g","carbs":"5g","fat":"12g","calories":"140 kcal"},"why":"A moderate portion of mixed nuts and seeds provides heart-protective unsaturated fats and magnesium, while soaked almonds are gentler on vata digestion.","substitutions":["Use flaxseeds instead of sunflower seeds","Use only walnuts and almonds if you prefer fewer varieties"]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Steamed Rice with Chana Dal Lauki Curry and Simple Kachumber","ingredients":["white or brown rice","chana dal","bottle gourd (lauki)","onion","tomato","ginger","garlic","turmeric powder","coriander powder","cumin seeds","rice bran oil","cucumber","tomato (for salad)","lemon juice","coriander leaves","salt (limited)","water"],"portion":"Rice 1 cup cooked (~150 g) + chana dal lauki 1.5 bowls (~250 g) + salad ~80 g","macros":{"protein":"19g","carbs":"78g","fat":"8g","calories":"480 kcal"},"why":"Chana dal with lauki adds soluble fiber and protein while being light and hydrating, and paired with rice it makes a complete, vata-friendly meal that supports heart health.","substitutions":["Use toor dal instead of chana dal","Use quinoa instead of rice for more protein"]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Hot Lemon-Coriander Soup with Vegetables","ingredients":["carrot","bottle gourd or pumpkin","tomato","coriander leaves","garlic","black pepper","lemon juice","olive oil or rice bran oil (1/2 tsp)","salt (limited)","water"],"portion":"1 medium bowl ~200 ml","macros":{"protein":"2g","carbs":"10g","fat":"2g","calories":"70 kcal"},"why":"Warm vegetable soup with coriander and lemon is soothing for vata, hydrating, and low in calories yet rich in antioxidants and potassium for heart health.","substitutions":["Use drumstick pieces instead of bottle gourd","Add a spoon of cooked barley for more body"]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"Rice and Urad Dal Dosa with Tomato-Onion Chutney","ingredients":["dosa batter (rice and urad dal fermented)","rice bran oil (for greasing)","tomato","onion","garlic","ginger","mustard seeds","curry leaves","red chili (small, optional)","salt (limited)","water"],"portion":"2 medium dosas (~160 g) + chutney 1 small bowl (~60 g)","macros":{"protein":"10g","carbs":"55g","fat":"7g","calories":"340 kcal"},"why":"Fermented dosa batter improves digestibility for vata, and when cooked with minimal oil it remains heart-friendly while providing complex carbs and some protein.","substitutions":["Use ragi dosa instead of rice dosa","Serve with sambar instead of chutney for more protein and fiber"]}}},{"day":6,"day_name":"Saturday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Vegetable Upma with Curry Leaves and Cashews","ingredients":["semolina (sooji)","rice bran oil or small amount of ghee","mustard seeds","curry leaves","onion","carrot","peas","ginger","green chili (optional, small)","cashews (few pieces)","water","salt (limited)","coriander leaves"],"portion":"1 medium bowl ~250 g","macros":{"protein":"8g","carbs":"55g","fat":"9g","calories":"360 kcal"},"why":"Soft, moist upma with vegetables and a few cashews gives sustained energy and is gentle on vata, while using moderate oil keeps the meal suitable for heart health.","substitutions":["Use broken wheat instead of semolina","Use almonds instead of cashews"]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Steamed Sweet Potato Chaat","ingredients":["sweet potato (steamed, cubed)","lemon juice","roasted cumin powder","black pepper","chopped coriander leaves","black salt (pinch)"],"portion":"1 small plate ~120 g","macros":{"protein":"2g","carbs":"28g","fat":"0g","calories":"120 kcal"},"why":"Sweet potato is grounding and sweet, ideal for vata, and its beta-carotene and fiber benefit cardiovascular health without raising blood sugar sharply when paired with spices.","substitutions":["Use boiled beetroot pieces instead of sweet potato","Mix with a few boiled chickpeas for extra protein"]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Jeera Rice with Mixed Dal Fry and Bhindi (Okra) Stir-Fry","ingredients":["white or brown rice","cumin seeds","mixed dals (toor, moong, masoor)","onion","tomato","garlic","ginger","turmeric powder","coriander powder","rice bran oil","okra (bhindi)","amchur powder (optional, small)","salt (limited)","coriander leaves","water"],"portion":"Jeera rice 1 cup cooked (~150 g) + dal 1.5 bowls (~250 g) + bhindi 1 bowl (~150 g)","macros":{"protein":"22g","carbs":"82g","fat":"10g","calories":"520 kcal"},"why":"Mixed dals and okra provide excellent fiber and plant protein supportive of cholesterol control, and the warm, mildly spiced dishes are balancing for vata.","substitutions":["Use quinoa instead of rice","Use methi bhaji instead of bhindi"]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Masala Chaas with Grated Carrot","ingredients":["low-fat curd","water","roasted cumin powder","finely grated carrot","coriander leaves","black salt (pinch)"],"portion":"1 glass ~220 ml","macros":{"protein":"4g","carbs":"7g","fat":"2g","calories":"60 kcal"},"why":"Spiced buttermilk with carrot supports digestion, hydration, and provides small amounts of beta-carotene while being gentle and pacifying for vata.","substitutions":["Use plain yogurt with water on the side if you don't like spices","Use grated cucumber instead of carrot"]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"One-Pot Vegetable Pulao with Moong and Nuts","ingredients":["basmati rice (preferably semi-polished or brown basmati)","split moong dal (soaked)","carrot","peas","beans (optional)","onion","ginger","garlic","bay leaf","cloves (1-2)","cinnamon (small piece)","rice bran oil or olive oil","almonds (slivered, few)","salt (limited)","coriander leaves","water"],"portion":"1 large bowl ~280 g","macros":{"protein":"14g","carbs":"72g","fat":"9g","calories":"450 kcal"},"why":"A lightly spiced pulao with moong and a few nuts offers a calm, grounding evening meal with complex carbs and plant protein supportive of heart health and vata stability.","substitutions":["Use quinoa instead of rice for more protein","Skip whole spices if they feel too strong and use only cumin"]}}},{"day":7,"day_name":"Sunday","meals":{"breakfast":{"dish_name":"Ragi Dosa with Potato-Drumstick Sambar","ingredients":["ragi flour","rice flour","urad dal (for fermentation, optional)","water","salt (limited)","rice bran oil (for greasing)","toor dal","drumstick pieces","small potato cubes","onion","tomato","tamarind (small amount)","sambar powder","turmeric powder","mustard seeds","curry leaves","coriander leaves"],"portion":"2 medium ragi dosas (~170 g) + sambar 1 bowl (~150 g)","macros":{"protein":"12g","carbs":"60g","fat":"7g","calories":"380 kcal"},"why":"Ragi adds calcium and fiber beneficial for heart and bone health, while warm sambar with drumstick and dal balances vata and supports steady energy.","substitutions":["Use plain rice dosa if ragi feels too heavy","Use pumpkin instead of potato in sambar"]},"morning_snack":{"dish_name":"Fresh Fruit Bowl with Cinnamon (Apple, Orange)","ingredients":["apple slices","orange segments","cinnamon powder","black pepper (pinch)"],"portion":"1 small bowl ~150 g","macros":{"protein":"1g","carbs":"30g","fat":"0g","calories":"120 kcal"},"why":"A small mix of apple and orange provides vitamin C, fiber, and natural sweetness, and adding cinnamon offers additional cardiometabolic benefits while keeping vata in check when fruits are not ice-cold.","substitutions":["Use guava instead of apple","Use pomegranate instead of orange"]},"lunch":{"dish_name":"Quinoa Vegetable Sambar-Rice Style Bowl","ingredients":["quinoa","toor dal","mixed vegetables (carrot, pumpkin, bottle gourd, drumstick)","onion","tomato","tamarind pulp (small)","sambar powder","turmeric powder","mustard seeds","curry leaves","rice bran oil","salt (limited)","coriander leaves","water"],"portion":"1 large bowl (quinoa + sambar mixed) ~320 g","macros":{"protein":"18g","carbs":"65g","fat":"8g","calories":"430 kcal"},"why":"Replacing rice with quinoa boosts protein and magnesium intake while sambar vegetables and dal provide fiber and micronutrients, all in a warm, soft dish compatible with vata and heart health.","substitutions":["Use brown rice instead of quinoa","Use moong dal instead of toor dal"]},"evening_snack":{"dish_name":"Warm Turmeric-Ginger Milk (Haldi Doodh) with a Date","ingredients":["low-fat cow's milk or fortified plant milk","turmeric powder","grated ginger (small piece)","black pepper (pinch)","1 Medjool date or 2 small dried dates"],"portion":"1 cup milk (~200 ml) + 1 date (~15 g)","macros":{"protein":"7g","carbs":"20g","fat":"4g","calories":"150 kcal"},"why":"Warm spiced milk grounds vata in the evening and turmeric-ginger offer anti-inflammatory and circulatory benefits relevant for long-term heart health, with a date for gentle sweetness.","substitutions":["Use almond milk instead of cow's milk","Use a small piece of jaggery instead of date"]},"dinner":{"dish_name":"Light Tomato-Drumstick Rasam with Steamed Rice and Simple Moong Subzi","ingredients":["white rice (well-cooked)","yellow moong dal (for rasam base and subzi)","drumstick pieces","tomato","garlic","mustard seeds","cumin seeds","black pepper","curry leaves","tamarind water (very small)","turmeric powder","rice bran oil or small ghee","grated coconut (very small, optional, for subzi)","salt (limited)","coriander leaves","water"],"portion":"Rice 1 cup cooked (~150 g) + rasam 1.5 bowls (~250 ml) + moong subzi 1 small bowl (~100 g)","macros":{"protein":"15g","carbs":"72g","fat":"6g","calories":"430 kcal"},"why":"A light, soupy rasam with rice is easy on digestion for vata on a Sunday night, while moong adds gentle protein and tomatoes, drumstick, and spices support circulation and heart health.","substitutions":["Use brown rice if digestion is strong","Skip coconut and use only dal in the subzi for fewer fats"]}}}]}
